ands, England":"Longueville, Jersey","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Duncan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: from the Older Scots personal name <i>Dunecan</i>, itself from the traditional Irish royal name <i>Donnchad(h)</i>, derived from <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’. Judging by the Scots form, the Scottish Gaelic intermediary seems to have been understood as containing <i>ceann</i> ‘head’, as if the whole name meant ‘brown head’; compare sense 2. In Ireland the name was Anglicized as <i>Donagh</i> or <i>Donaghue</i>. Compare   Donahue  .","Irish: used as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donncheann</i>’, a byname composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>ceann</i> ‘head’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duncanson","meanings":["Scottish: from the Scottish personal name   Duncan   + <i>son</i> ‘son of Duncan’."]},{"name":"Dinkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Isador.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic, with the addition of the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>, from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Dinke</i>, a hypocoristic form of Biblical <i>Dinah</i>, from Hebrew <i>dina</i> ‘judged, vindicated’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> (see   Duncan   2)."]},{"name":"Donkin","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): northeastern English variant of Scottish   Duncan  ."]},{"name":"Donahue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Siobhan, Aileen, Conan, Fidelma, John Patrick, Kieran, Parnell.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Donnchadha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donnchadh</i>’, a personal name (sometimes Anglicized as <i>Duncan</i> in Scotland), composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Dunkin","meanings":["Manx: variant of   Duncan  .","Irish (Fermanagh): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> (see   Duncan  )."]}]},{"name":"Cameron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:","in the Highlands, it is usually a nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>sròn</i> ‘nose’.","in the Lowlands it is also a habitational name from any of various places called Cameron, especially in Fife."],"variants":[{"name":"Camren","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Cameron  ."]},{"name":"Cambron","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Cambrón</b>): habitational name from any of several places in the provinces of Cáceres and Murcia called Cambrón.","Scottish: altered form of   Cameron  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Somme and Aisne called Cambron. Alternatively, from a diminutive of <i>c(h)ambre</i> ‘room’ (see   Cambre  )."]},{"name":"Camron","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Cameron  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":23,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":43,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":53,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs George Duncan Cameron was born about 1043, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with George Duncan."},"et":{"about 1043–":"umbes 1043–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1063–1154":"1063–1154","1043–Female":"1043–Surnud","1066":"1066","1154":"1154","1043":"1043","1086":"1086","1063":"1063","1096":"1096","about 1043":"umbes 1043","1040":"1